I"W<h4 id="to-stain-the-blank-page-on-blogging-and-the-ships-log-through-the-figure-of-the-binnacle">To stain the blank page: on blogging and the shipâ€™s log, through the figure of the binnacle.</h4>

<p>What is it to <del>start</del> resume blogging now, in the spring of 2023? (Other than it no longer being 1998, that is.) It seems uncertainty is the order of the day. Some speak of a â€œ<a href="https://www.unpopularfront.news/p/have-you-heard-about-the-polycrisis">polycrisis</a>â€, while bracing for further ruptures amid mounting turbulence. The digital leviathans founder, the public sphere takes damage, giving way to a froth of invite-only backchannels and social dark pools. Early ripples, perhaps, of <a href="https://www.are.na/justin-pickard/epistemic-breakdown">epistemic breakdown</a>; a peeling-apart of our criteria for appraising truth amid information overload, new synthetic media, and a multiply-breached social contract.</p>

<p>Today, the web is no longer new media, but the backdrop, staging, and atmospherics of lives lived online. Blog is a clipping of a kenning, hinging the network and the archive. And if the novelty of the web is fast-fading, then we should be places more stress on the <em>log</em> half of that hinge.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/2023-04-20-binnacle.jpg" alt="Compass in binnacle, George Stebbing, 1819" /></p>

<p>As a format and genre, the weblog is haunted by the shipâ€™s log. Initially, this was a record of readings from the chip log; a piece of wood on a length of rope, used to calculate a shipâ€™s speed. And both of these logs frequently found their way into the binnacle.</p>

<p>Originally a kind of open cupboard, the binnacle usually had separate compartments for compass, lamp, and hourglass â€” a composite interface of handheld tools, permitting the seafarer to orient themselves (and their vessel) in space and time.</p>

<p>Beyond its actual use, the binnacle was a convenient container for ship documents and equipment of all kinds:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€˜Captain Cook kept the keys of the leg-irons in the binnacle, while Captain Bligh thought his a suitable stowage for a pair of pistols.â€™ (May, 1954: 28)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The shipâ€™s log existed alongside navigation devices, and â€˜within the drifts of other documents on board a typical shipâ€™ (Schotte, 2013: 284). More prominent than other written media, it was neither outlier nor exception â€” only important inasmuch as it enabled (successful) navigation. Initially intended for personal use during voyages, 16th- and 17th-century log-keepers sought flexibility and simplicity, from a â€˜methodical, concise, and adaptable document, validated by daily useâ€™ (ibid: 292).</p>

<p>These navigator-practitioners adopted the shipâ€™s log to cope with â€˜increasing quantities of information â€¦ in an age when the scale of their oceanic crossings required them to coordinate ever more informationâ€™ (Schotte, 2013: 290). But as anthropologist Nick Seaver notes, stories about information overload are as much about shifts in the â€˜scalar relationship between archives and individualsâ€™ as any shared, objective reality:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Overload requires more than an overwhelming amount of stuff; it requires someone to feel overwhelmed (Seaver, 2023: 36-37).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In a context of information overload, thinking with the binnacle shows how the blog, like the shipâ€™s log, is an epistemic genre; a class or category of texts linked (in their authorsâ€™ eyes, at least) to the dance of knowledge-making. (see <a href="https://doi.org/10.1353/lm.2014.0010">Pomata, 2014</a>) For me, the motivation is less about â€˜<a href="https://www.robinsloan.com/lab/new-avenues/">working with the garage door open</a>â€™ than logging an itinerary â€” discerning and recording information, as a personal navigation aid; and for the benefit of those traversing the same (or similarly) turbulent waters.</p>

